blueprint/src/chapters/AbelJacobi.tex:80:  \emph{Lean closure.} By Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, the Jacobian $\Jac(C)$ is, uniformly in the marked point $P$, the underlying scheme of an Albanese witness for the pointed curve $(C, P)$: it carries an Albanese structure $\mathrm{IsAlbanese}\,C\,P\,\Jac(C)$ in the sense of Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}, whose universal pointed morphism is the Abel--Jacobi map $\alpha_P$ of Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve} (with $\alpha_P \circ P = \eta_{\Jac(C)}$ being Lemma~\ref{lem:comp_ofCurve}). The universal-property data carried by this Albanese structure is, by Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}, exactly the existence-and-uniqueness assertion of the theorem: for every $f \colon C \to A$ with $f \circ P = \eta_A$, there is a unique $g \colon \Jac(C) \to A$ with $f = \alpha_P \circ g$. The Lean side closes the goal by projecting this universal-property field of the Albanese witness $\mathrm{IsAlbanese}\,C\,P\,\Jac(C)$, applied to the data $(f, hf)$.
blueprint/src/chapters/AbelJacobi.tex:82:  \emph{Classical description.} The classical proof of the same statement proceeds in two parts. In positive genus ($g(C) > 0$), the existence and uniqueness of the factorisation come from the Pic-scheme representability theorem together with the Stein factorisation of the Abel--Jacobi morphism: see Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, Route~A (sub-steps A.1--A.4) for the line-bundle / universal-property route via $\Pic^0_{C/k}$, and Route~B (sub-steps B.1--B.3) for the symmetric-power / Stein-factorisation route. In genus $0$, the same statement reduces to the rigidity theorem for $C \to A$ established \emph{directly over $k$} --- the named declaration \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} of \cref{chap:RigidityKbar}, whose signature is $k$-agnostic per the iter-127 over-k commitment (\texttt{analogies/cotangent-vanishing-pile-over-k.md}) and which is built out of the shared cotangent-vanishing pile pieces (i)+(ii)+(iii) over an arbitrary base field with no algebraic-closure, perfect-base, or Galois-descent hypothesis. See Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, sub-cases C.1--C.3, in particular the seven-step expansion C.2.a--C.2.g, where sub-step C.2.f (Galois descent of morphism equality back to $k$) is \textbf{DROPPED} under the iter-127 commitment: no base-change-and-descent step appears anywhere in the M2 critical path. The protected signature of Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} does \emph{not} assume $C(k) \neq \emptyset$, so the genus-$0$ argument branches on whether a $k$-rational point exists. When $C(k) \neq \emptyset$, the supplied $P \in C(k)$ feeds the pointing hypothesis of \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} directly --- no $C \cong \mathbb P^1_k$ identification is required, sidestepping the Brauer--Severi obstruction (Brauer--Severi conics over $\mathbb Q$ are the standard counterexample to an unconditional $k$-side identification). When $C(k) = \emptyset$, the $\mathtt{isAlbaneseFor}$ field of the genus-$0$ witness (\cref{def:genusZeroWitness}) is vacuously true at the Lean type level: the universal quantifier $\forall\, (P \colon \mathbf{1} \to C)$ ranges over the empty type. None of this classical content is replayed in the Lean formalisation: it is bundled into the deferred existence hypothesis Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, whose proof is the project's single explicit foundational gap.
blueprint/src/chapters/AbelJacobi.tex:87:The three results above are formalised through the Albanese framework of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}. In the absence of Mathlib's Pic-scheme machinery, the Jacobian is defined (Layer~I) as the underlying scheme of an Albanese witness uniform in the marked point (Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}); the universal-property data $(\iota_P,\, \text{factorisation})$ is then carried by the Albanese predicate (Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}) and projects directly into the three results of this chapter (Layer~II): the Abel--Jacobi map $\alpha_P := \iota_P$ of Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve}, its pointed property of Lemma~\ref{lem:comp_ofCurve}, and the universal factorisation of Theorem~\ref{thm:exists_unique_ofCurve_comp}. Existence of a uniform-over-$P$ Albanese object is the single remaining mathematical hypothesis pending the formalisation of either Pic-scheme representability (Route~A), symmetric-power quotients plus Stein factorisation (Route~B), or rigidity for $C \to A$ established \emph{directly over $k$} (genus-$0$ sub-case, via \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} per the iter-127 over-k commitment; no base-change to $\bar k$ and no Galois descent of morphism equality enter, and sub-step C.2.f of \S~C.2 is correspondingly DROPPED).
blueprint/src/chapters/AbelJacobi.tex:89:The classical proof via line bundles --- using the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$, dual abelian varieties, and (for the genus-$0$ sub-case) rigidity for $C \to A$ established directly over $k$ via \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} (per the iter-127 over-k commitment; no base-change to $\bar k$ and no Galois descent of morphism equality enter) --- gives the same conclusions but requires more Mathlib infrastructure than is presently available, as catalogued in the proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} and the milestone roadmap of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}. The Albanese-framework route used here is mathematically equivalent and bundles all of the missing infrastructure into that single deferred existence hypothesis.
